Europe
------
[1] Russia (Astrakhan)
Date: Sat 2 Jul 2011
Source: Kavkazskiy Uzyel News Agency [in Russian, trans. Corr.ATS,
edited]
http://www.kavkaz-uzel.ru/articles/188327/


17 people in Astrakhan have been diagnosed with measles. These cases
are the 1st after a 3-year break. The region was considered to be
measles-free; however, 8 adults and 9 children have been diagnosed
with measles recently. The local public health authorities consider
the cases to be imported cases, and blame the primary healthcare
system for a failure to maintain an adequate level of immunization in
the population.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-RUS
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Astrakhan oblast is a federal subject of the Russian Federation,
part of the Southern Federal District. The administrative center and
capital is Astrakhan city. The region is in the Caspian lowland where
the Volga River flows into Caspian Sea. The largest part of Astrakhan
oblast consists of semi-deserts. A map showing the location of the
Astrakhan oblast can be found at:
http://russiatrek.org/astrakhan-oblast. It is a boundary territory
and hence open to importation of infection. - Mod.CP]

******
[2] Switzerland
Date: Tue 5 Jul 2011
Source: World Radio Switzerland [edited]
http://worldradio.ch/wrs/news/wrsnews/swiss-measles-outbreak-lingers.shtml?25403


Swiss federal health officials say the measles epidemic which broke
out earlier this year [2011] is still ongoing, although at a slower
pace. Officials registered 44 cases of measles in just 4 days,
Jean-Louis Zurcher, a spokesman for the Federal Office of Public
Health, told public television recently.

So far, there have been more than 600 cases of measles this year
[2011], mostly affecting the cantons of Geneva, Vaud, Graubunden,
Zurich and Bern. Last year [2010], there were only about 30 cases in
the 1st half of the year.

The peak of the epidemic occurred in April 2011, when 205 cases were
recorded, Zurcher said. He said 9 out of every 10 cases involve people
who were not vaccinated.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A map showing the locations of the cantons of Switzerland can be
found at: http://www.rollintl.com/roll/switzerland.htm. Switzerland
is particularly vulnerable to importation of infection in view of its
central location in Europe and its large population of non-residents
and temporary visitors. - Mod.CP]

