The Americas
----------
[5] Mexico (Jalisco)
Date: Wed 6 Jul 2011
Source: El Occidental [in Spanish, machine trans., abbreviated &
edited]
http://www.oem.com.mx/eloccidental/notas/n2135514.htm


The Ministry of Health of Jalisco (SSJ) has declared a measles alert
as a consequence of the current epidemic in Europe and is advising all
persons aged one year to 39 years of age to be vaccinated.

Although Jalisco has had 16 years with no cases of measles, an
epidemic alert is warranted in the vicinity of the capital
Guadalajara, the location of the 2011 Pan American Games and various
other international events organised by the state, which will attract
foreign tourists. The Minister of Public Health, Mario Amezcua
Marquez, said that since last Friday's [1 Jul 2011] federal health
agency alert, surveillance and vaccination in the state had been
enhanced. The health official said that the measles vaccination rate
is high in Jalisco state, but those uncertain of their vaccination
status should seek vaccination.

The outbreak in Europe has affected 24 countries with about 6500
cases, according to the World Health Organization (WHO), affecting
adversely the prospects for global eradication of the disease. The
director general of the SSJ Public Health Department attributed the
problem to those European countries, such as France and Germany, that
do not have mandatory vaccination policies, a situation that must
change if the disease is to be eradicated.

In the Americas from January to May this year [2011], 336 cases have
been recorded in Canada, USA, Chile, Brazil, Panama, Dominican
Republic and Argentina, but none has occurred so far in Mexico.

[Byline: Isaura Lopez Villalobos]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[A similar alert was issued in the southern state of Tabasco on Thu 7
Jul 2010, likewise recommending travelers to the United States or
Europe to review urgently their vaccination status and seek
vaccination if appropriate. According to the Director of Preventive
Health Programs, Ramon de Jesus Velarde Ayala, measles had been
eliminated in Mexico for several decades, and vaccine coverage in the
Tabasco state exceeded 99.9 per cent. See the Milenio online report
at: http://impreso.milenio.com/node/8988286. - Mod.CP]

******
[6] USA (Florida)
Date: Fri 8 Jul 2011
Source: St Petersburg Times [edited]
http://www.tampabay.com/news/health/as-more-parents-opt-their-kids-out-of-vaccination-florida-measles-cases/1179329


The back-to-school push for children's vaccinations has new urgency
this year [2011] as Florida health officials report an alarming rise
in measles. So far this year, 7 cases have been reported in Florida,
the most in 14 years. All but one involved an unvaccinated child 1-16
years old. Most of the children's parents had exempted them from
state-required vaccinations by citing religious objections to
vaccines.

More and more parents in the Tampa Bay area and around Florida are
claiming such objections. But medical experts say they think the real
issue often is not religion, but unfounded fears of a connection
between vaccines and autism. Cost, they say, should never be a factor.
Parents who can't afford a doctor visit can take their children to
county health department clinics or to a back-to-school immunization
event. And insurance covers vaccinations.

"We would just encourage parents to start thinking now about what
their child needs for school and not to wait until the last minute,"
said Maggie Hall, spokeswoman for the Pinellas County Health
Department. Parents who wait until just before school starts may face
long waits for vaccines required for school. But the health community
is more concerned about the small but growing number of parents who
refuse vaccines for children.

The measles vaccine, which comes in a shot that also protects against
the mumps and rubella, has never contained thimerosal, the
preservative that generated particular concern in the vaccines debate
(although even thimerosal has been cleared of any autism connection).

Still, some parents don't appear convinced. In the past decade, the
number of Florida kindergarten students whose parents claim religious
exemptions has more than quadrupled, state records show. About 2400
kindergartners statewide have religious exemptions for the current
school year. Four of the 6 children in Florida who got the measles
this year [2011] had a religious exemption to the school immunization
requirement.

Given all the debate, the Catholic Diocese of St. Petersburg has
recently clarified the church's position. In a letter to pastors and
parochial school principals, Bishop Robert Lynch said the church does
not teach that using vaccines is "intrinsically evil," even if the
vaccine was produced with controversial stem cell lines. [As far as
this moderator is aware, no commercial MMR vaccine is produced in stem
cell cultures. - Mod.CP]. So Catholic schools shouldn't grant vaccine
exemptions on religious grounds.

Health experts fear that many people have forgotten just how bad
measles can be, since the vaccine has made the disease so rare [in the
Americas] in recent decades. Measles remains one of the most
contagious diseases, said Dr. Juan Dumois, chairman of infectious
diseases at All Children's Hospital in St. Petersburg. It can be
acquired by breathing in air in the vicinity of a measles patient
without being right next to him or her.

About 10 days after exposure, patients who contract the infection
start to develop a fever, cough, congestion and red eyes. The
tell-tale measles rash, which starts on the face and spreads to the
body, shows up 3 to 4 days later. Many doctors today struggle to
recognize the disease because they've never seen a case.

Most children recover in about a week, but some young patients will
stop eating and drinking, requiring hospitalization and intravenous
fluids. About one in 1000 develops a brain infection that can lead to
permanent neurological damage, if they survive, and one or 2 in 1000
die. "You never know when your child is going to be the one in 1000,"
Dumois said. "It's sort of like playing roulette, hoping that your
child won't be the one who suffers, if the argument is, 'Well, measles
isn't so bad in most of the children who get it.' And a stricken child
could pass the virus on to an elderly relative or someone else who
lacks a strong immune system. For them, the disease can be especially
dangerous."

So far this year [2011], almost all of the Florida cases were linked
to travel, as has been the case nationally. The 156 cases reported
this year by the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
represent a 15-year high. With measles hot spots seen in Europe,
Africa, India and Southeast Asia, authorities recommend that U.S.
residents traveling overseas get immunized. That means 2 doses of the
measles vaccine for anyone one year or older, Dumois said, and one
dose for infants between 6 and 11 months. The travel advisory calls
for earlier immunizations than the typical schedule. Children usually
get their 1st measles shot at 12 to 15 months, with the 2nd at 4 to 6
years

[Byline: Letitia Stein]

--
