[8] USA (New York)
Date: Sun 10 Jul 2011
Source: Democrat and Chronicle.com [edited]
http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20110709/NEWS01/110709005


The Seneca County Health Department has confirmed that a student at
New York Chiropractic College is a case of measles. This viral disease
is airborne and highly contagious. A spokeswoman said the Seneca
County Health Department is working with the New York State Department
of Health as well as the college to implement control measures to
prevent the disease from spreading throughout the community.

Individuals may have been exposed to measles if they visited the
following locations on the dates and times listed below:

26 Jun 2011:
- Wegmans, 300 Hamilton Street, Geneva, NY 4 p.m. to 8:30 p.m.
- Happy Family, 84 Fall Street, Seneca Falls 6 p.m. to 9:30 p.m.

27 Jun 2011:
- Seneca Falls Health Center at the New York State Chiropractic
College, 2360 Route 89, Seneca Falls 7 a.m. to 6:30 p.m.
- Cafeteria at the New York Chiropractic College 10 a.m. to 3 p.m.

28 Jun 2011:
- Walmart (Seneca Falls), 1860 North Road Waterloo, NY 6 p.m. to 10
p.m.

29 Jun 2011:
- Seneca Falls Health Center at the New York State Chiropractic
College 8 a.m. to 8 p.m.
- Cafeteria at the New York Chiropractic College 10 a.m. to 7 p.m.

30 Jun 2011:
- Seneca Falls Health Center at the New York State Chiropractic
College 7 a.m. to 6 p.m.
- Cafeteria at the New York Chiropractic College 10 a.m. to 3 p.m.
- Starbucks, Route 81, N. Watertown NY 4 p.m. to 7 p.m.

Airborne droplets remain active and contagious on infected surfaces
for up to 2 hours. Individuals are advised to contact their primary
care physician and notify the Seneca County Health Department if they
develop symptoms of measles that progressively worsen over the course
of 7 days. The department can be reached at (315) 539-1920, after
hours at (315) 246-0558 or online at http://www.co.seneca.ny.us/ or
http://www.health.state.ny.us/.

--
